Introduction ¶

Dataset Source ¶

The heart rate dataset used in this study is sourced from Kaggle (Mirza_Hasnine, 2023). This dataset contains the risk factors that can contribute to a heart stroke.

Dataset Details ¶

This dataset is about the risk factors that plays a major role in causing a heart disease to a person.

The dataset contains information about the risk factors like smoking, increase hypertension, total cholesterol levels and also about the glucose levels. Additional features included in this dataset are the age, BMI, gender, education level of the person, number of cigarettes smoked per day(if the person is smoking), BP medicines taken, systolic and diastolic blood pressure levels, heart rate, if the person has diabetes and if they have any prevalence of stroke. These features appear to be suffice for us to make an attempt for predictive modeling of heart disease as a classification problem.

This dataset has a total of 16 features and 4238 observations.

Target Feature ¶

For this project, the target feature in this dataset will be the Heart_ stroke feature. It is a categorical feature which will be predicted based on the other descriptive variables by classification modeling algorithms.

Goals and Objectives ¶

Cardio vascular diseases are one of the primary reason that causes mortality globally. There are various types of heart diseases like heart attacks, cardiac arrhythmia and so on that are caused by different factors. Heart attack is caused when the supply of blood to the heart is blocked. It is important to identify the risk factors that are causing these diseases and create a model that would be able to predict the on-set of these diseases. Hence as part of our project we are trying to analyze the various risk factors and if they have any impact to the heart stroke occurrences.

The given dataset contains the medical records of 4238 patients. The medical records include various clinical variables like age, gender, BMI, total cholesterol, Glucose level, Heart rate, smoking habits and stroke prevalence. With the help of these variables we will try to model the dataset and predict the occurrence of heart stroke. As part of this project we will try to do our analysis on 2 major aspects. The primary objective is to predict the occurrence of heart stroke based on the set of clinical features and the next is to identify which of these features appears to be the best predictors of the heart stroke occurrence. The primary objective will be carried out later in phase 2, whereas in this phase 1 we will try to understand the relationships of these features by performing some exploratory data analysis with the help of descriptive statistics and data visualization plots.

To perform this phase 1 analysis, we will start with understanding the data and perform some data preprocessing activity and then go further with the data exploration.

Summary and Conclusions ¶

In Phase 1 of our project, we have taken a public heart disease dataset with the clinical features of the patients as the variables. Initially, we performed data preprocessing tasks like data cleaning, data processing, and visualizing the data. First, we have explored the variables and shape of the chosen dataset. While checking for null or missing values, we have found that variables like 'education', 'cigsPerDay', 'BPMeds', 'totChol', 'BMI', 'heartRate', and 'glucose' contains null values. We have replaced the null values with mode value, and mean value and dropped null values for few variables as shown above. Once after cleaning the data, we verified again whether the dataset still have any other missing values. We have also verified the dataset if it contains any duplicate/incorrect values. Besides, we have made data type conversions for 'cigsPerDay', and 'BPMeds'.

Once we have completed the data cleaning and processing tasks, we made several data visualization for uni-variable, bi-variable, and multi-variables. Using these data visualizations we could clearly say that more females at a later age have suffered heart stroke when compared to males and we have observed that blood pressure and glucose level are independent features when correlating the occurrence of heart stroke of an individual. Hence, the clinical features are fluctuating between the gender and the medical condition of the patient.

We will be exploring more about the dataset to perform tasks like Data preparation and implementing machine learning algorithms to the dataset to predict which clinical feature is the best predictor for heart stroke in Phase 2 of the project.

Literature Review ¶

Classification data represents one among the possible most popular jobs for machine learning techniques. The ability to extract information gathered from datasets of business activities and transmit it to broader databases seems to be crucial in this situation. The bulk underlying machine learning techniques rely on an enormous number of features to describe the behavior of the technique, which either directly or through inference increases the level of difficulty of any model being trained. However, Python's use in the field business health care is greatly benefited by the way it applies machine learning as well as artificial intelligence to help make meaning out of the statistics being analyzed.

Machine Learning's main objective is to construct systems, let them study, as well as then use what they learned to generate predictions. It builds a model by preparing machine learning techniques on a sample dataset. The system forecasts heart disease using the new incoming data. It creates models employing machine learning towards findinghidden correlations in the provided dataset. It generates precise forecasts for fresh datasets. Missing values are filled in once the dataset has been cleansed. The model forecasts heart disease using the new information provided, and its precision is subsequently evaluated.

By examining the risk factors of coronary artery disease via patient's data, it is possible to effectively predict the occurrence of heart attack. Methods for data mining are utilized across a variety of areas. Data mining was crucial in medical fields for predicting cardiac disease. For each condition to be diagnosed, doctors must do a variety of tests. However, heart disease detection cut down on work and produced reliable findings.

BMI may be linked to an increased risk of developing heart disease in general. However, a lot of research only appear to address the issue in more generic ways. A connection involving heart attacks or BMI has been shown in earlier observational studies. They looked at 899 obese people among the ages of 3574. The researchers came to the conclusion that being overweight or obese was neither an independently observed standalone cardiovascular risk indicator after ten years of monitoring. Due to the limited sample magnitude, this research's statistical strength is inadequate. Additionally, similar to other empirical investigations, it may have confounding issues (such as cigarette and liquor usage) and other forms of bias. Outcomes of these investigations are of limited relevance since clinical therapy development need the identification of precise causative elements.

AMI (Acute Myocardial Infarction) was subsequently detected in a significant fraction of patients, especially approximately half of those women, who refused to initially complain of discomfort in their chests. The majority of the gendered disparities in presentation, especially in children and adolescents, are explained by the existence of co-morbid illnesses, which reduce the probability that chest pain would be the primary complaint.

These findings imply that tobacco use is an essential component in the connection between periodontal gum disease as well as heart attacks and strokes, and the chance of developing it is believed to grow with age. It is challenging to evaluate what percentage of the observed connection was caused by periodontist diseases, though, given the significant role smoking plays in the aetiology of both restoration and cardiac illnesses.

Studies have supported the association between greater BMI along with a higher perceived risk of mellitus alongside heart attack as well as any family background of diabetes or an early heart attack. A few subjects reported a twofold risk of developing diabetes or cardiac arrest despite similar risk factors, although age along with physical fitness were not related to both risk perception. Proper assessment of one's risk due to diabetes as well as cardiovascular disease is the crucial initial step in making these lifestyle adjustments, but preventing diabetic complications and heart attacks demands drive and dedication. Health care professionals must evaluate the differences between person's perceived risk as well as the lack of actual danger indicators and educate patients about the link between being diabetic and getting heart attacks.
